And more! 

  MADELEINE: I’ll share what I know. John Smith led a rather colourful life, fighting bravely in wars across the world before landing the job of ‘president’ of the Jamestown colony in newly ‘discovered’ Virginia. The story goes that while out exploring, John Smith was captured by the ruling Powhatan tribe. He testifies that they were about to kill him when the Chief’s daughter Pocahontas pleaded for his life. She was 11. So stories of their love are hopefully fabrications!
  John Smith was instrumental in mapping out the region and helping the settlers survive their new environment. He was generally considered better than other colonists, trading with the local Powhatan community. Some accounts state good relations with the tribe. But others talk of him waging attacks on natives for refusing to give up their limited winter food stock without at least some payment. Captain John Smith ordered the burning of their villages, imprisoned and beat native people, and forced them into labour. He was considered a national hero in his time - but how do you see him now? Hero or villain?

