<<timed 1s>><<replace "#mount">> DOROTHEA: Celebrating the deeds of ordinary people is a great gesture. But how often does it spark a lasting change in their lives?

This park was built in 1900. Class divides in this country were (and still are) enormous. There are women in our movement who are expected to work dangerous, exhausting jobs in factories, care for their children and keep their husbands happy by being impeccable housewives. If they are arrested, they risk losing everything. But still they come. To every march.

There are also women in our movement who live in grand houses and are expected to do little more than dress prettily for balls and make a good marriage. If they are arrested, there is always someone to pay their bail (albeit reluctantly) and take them back home to relative comfort. Yes, both women make sacrifices. Yes, they are both heroic. But they are part of a bigger battle for change. A single act of sacrifice - well that is easily missed, just like the names on that wall. A thousand women led into battle by a powerful leader - that is not so easily forgot.

So I ask, should we commemorate ordinary acts of sacrifice with monuments like this? Or should we fight for a world where the sacrifices are not needed? What do you think? Let your imagination run free. Discuss it together and share your answer - I’d love to hear!
  
